The Chronicle Sikhumbuzo Moyo, Senior Sports Reporter
NATIONAL University of Science and Technology (Nust) will play host to the 2022 edition of the Zimbabwe Universities Sports Association (Zusa) Games from today up to Saturday. The games, to be contested over nine sport codes, will have a record 16 universities from around the country. Last year’s games were won by Midlands State University, which hosted the competitions, with University of Zimbabwe and Nust emerging first and second runners-up respectively.  According to Judy Siziba, the local organising committee chairperson, sport codes on offer are athletics, table tennis, chess, cricket, golf, hockey, karate, tennis and rugby. “Athletics, table tennis, karate and chess will be at Nust, while the remaining codes will be held in facilities around the city (Bulawayo),” said Siziba. Golf will be at Harry Allen Golf Course, hockey at Khumalo Hockey Stadium, cricket at Bulawayo Athletic Club, Busters and McDonald’s, tennis will be at BAC while Hartsfield will play host to rugby. The Zusa Games are part of the journey that will see the staging of the Zimbabwe Tertiary Institution Students’ Union (Zitusu) Games where a squad will be selected to represent Zimbabwe in the World Universities Games. Participating Universities
Africa University, Bindura University of Science Education, Chinhoyi University of Technology, Catholic University in Zimbabwe, Gwanda State University, Great Zimbabwe University, Harare Institute of Technology, Lupane State University, Midlands State University, Manicaland University of Applied Sciences, Marondera University of Agricultural Sciences and Technology, Nust, Reformed Church University, Women’s University in Africa, University of Zimbabwe and Zimbabwe Ezekiel Guti University